## ✨ CHANGE 7 — Loops Email Suite (Premium Voice Edition)

**Goal:** Twelve lifecycle emails rewritten as personal letters from Lauren. Most of this work happens in Loops itself (you'll paste these in directly). Claude Code's role is wiring the trigger events from the app to Loops.

**Important:** The email *content* below is for Lauren to paste into Loops directly. Claude Code's responsibility for this change is only:
1. Building the `/api/loops-event.js` proxy endpoint
2. Adding `fireMilestoneEvent()` calls at the right moments in the app
3. Ensuring user properties (firstName, planCount, captionCount, etc.) are synced to Loops

### 7a. Build the `/api/loops-event.js` proxy endpoint

Create this file in `/api/loops-event.js`:

```javascript
// /api/loops-event.js
// Proxy endpoint that fires a Loops event for the current user.
// Used by the frontend to trigger lifecycle emails.

module.exports = async function handler(req, res) {
  if (req.method !== "POST") {
    return res.status(405).json({ error: "Method not allowed" });
  }

  const apiKey = process.env.LOOPS_API_KEY;

  // Graceful degradation — if Loops isn't configured, log and return ok
  if (!apiKey) {
    console.warn("[loops-event] LOOPS_API_KEY not set");
    return res.status(200).json({ ok: true, note: "Loops not configured" });
  }

  const { userId, email, eventName, properties } = req.body || {};

  if (!eventName || (!userId && !email)) {
    return res.status(400).json({ error: "eventName and userId or email required" });
  }

  try {
    const response = await fetch("https://app.loops.so/api/v1/events/send", {
      method: "POST",
      headers: {
        "Authorization": "Bearer " + apiKey,
        "Content-Type": "application/json",
      },
      body: JSON.stringify({
        userId: userId,
        email: email,
        eventName: eventName,
        eventProperties: properties || {},
      }),
    });

    if (!response.ok) {
      console.warn("[loops-event] Loops returned " + response.status);
      return res.status(200).json({ ok: false });
    }

    return res.status(200).json({ ok: true });
  } catch (err) {
    console.error("[loops-event] error:", err.message);
    return res.status(200).json({ ok: false });
  }
};
```

### 7b. Add the helper function in `index.html`

Add near the existing API helpers (around the existing `callAPI` function):

```javascript
async function fireLoopsEvent(eventName, properties) {
  if (!session || !session.user) return;
  try {
    await fetch("/api/loops-event", {
      method: "POST",
      headers: { "Content-Type": "application/json" },
      body: JSON.stringify({
        userId: session.user.id,
        email: session.user.email,
        eventName: eventName,
        properties: properties || {},
      }),
    });
  } catch (e) {
    console.warn("[loops] event failed:", e);
  }
}
```

### 7c. Wire the events at the right moments

Add `fireLoopsEvent` calls at these points:

| Trigger point | Event name | Properties |
|---|---|---|
| User signs up | `userSignedUp` | `firstName` |
| 24h after signup, profile not complete | (nightly job — Loops handles this from properties) | sync `profileComplete: false` to Loops |
| First plan generation | `firstPlanGenerated` | `firstName`, `planCount: 1` |
| Plan #5 generated | `fivePlansMilestone` | `firstName`, `planCount: 5` |
| Plan #10 generated | `tenPlansMilestone` | `firstName`, `planCount: 10` |
